Now we substitute $ \sin y = \frac{1}{3} $ into our formula:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos 2y &= 1 - 2\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 \\
&= 1 - 2\left(\frac{1}{9}\right) \\
&= 1 - \frac{2}{9} \\
&= \frac{7}{9}
\end{aligned}
$$

Substitute $ \cos 2y = \frac{7}{9} $ into the expression:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos 4y &= 2\left(\frac{7}{9}\right)^2 - 1 \\
&= 2\left(\frac{49}{81}\right) - 1 \\
&= \frac{98}{81} - \frac{81}{81} \\
&= \frac{17}{81}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, we substitute $ \sin y = \frac{1}{3} $ into our derived formula.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos 4y &= 1 - 8\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 + 8\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^4 \\
&= 1 - 8\left(\frac{1}{9}\right) + 8\left(\frac{1}{81}\right) \\
&= 1 - \frac{8}{9} + \frac{8}{81}
\end{aligned}
$$

We solve the fraction arithmetic by finding a common denominator of 81:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos 4y &= \frac{81}{81} - \frac{72}{81} + \frac{8}{81} \\
&= \frac{81 - 72 + 8}{81} \\
&= \frac{17}{81}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Answer:** $ \cos 4y = \frac{17}{81} $

